{"parse":{"title":"Dreamachine","pageid":5792336,"revid":860191951,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">This article is about the stroboscopic device. For the album by John Zorn, see <a href=\"/wiki/Dreamachines\" title=\"Dreamachines\">Dreamachines</a>. For the psychedelic rock band, see <a href=\"/wiki/Matthew_Melton\" title=\"Matthew Melton\">Matthew Melton</a>.</div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:202px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Dreamachine_still_lit.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b9/Dreamachine_still_lit.jpg/200px-Dreamachine_still_lit.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"267\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b9/Dreamachine_still_lit.jpg/300px-Dreamachine_still_lit.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b9/Dreamachine_still_lit.jpg/400px-Dreamachine_still_lit.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2153\" data-file-height=\"2870\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Dreamachine_still_lit.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>A homemade dreamachine, lit internally</div></div></div>\n<p>The <b>Dreamachine</b> (or <b>Dream Machine</b>) is a <a href=\"/wiki/Stroboscope\" title=\"Stroboscope\">stroboscopic</a> flicker device that produces visual stimuli. Artist <a href=\"/wiki/Brion_Gysin\" title=\"Brion Gysin\">Brion Gysin</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/William_S._Burroughs\" title=\"William S. Burroughs\">William S. Burroughs</a>' \"systems adviser\" <a href=\"/wiki/Ian_Sommerville_(technician)\" title=\"Ian Sommerville (technician)\">Ian Sommerville</a> created the Dreamachine after reading <a href=\"/wiki/William_Grey_Walter\" title=\"William Grey Walter\">William Grey Walter</a>' book, <i>The Living Brain</i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Cecil_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Cecil-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Century_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Century-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Use\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Use</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Notes\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Notes</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#Further_reading\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Further reading</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-7\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">7</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Dreamachine&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In its original form, a Dreamachine is made from a cylinder with slits cut in the sides.  The cylinder is placed on a <a href=\"/wiki/Phonograph\" title=\"Phonograph\">record turntable</a> and rotated at 78 or 45 <a href=\"/wiki/Revolutions_per_minute\" title=\"Revolutions per minute\">revolutions per minute</a>. A light bulb is suspended in the center of the cylinder and the rotation speed allows the light to come out from the holes at a constant frequency of between 8 and 13 pulses per second. This frequency range corresponds to <a href=\"/wiki/Alpha_wave\" title=\"Alpha wave\">alpha waves</a>, electrical <a href=\"/wiki/Oscillation\" title=\"Oscillation\">oscillations</a> normally present in the human brain while <a href=\"/wiki/Relaxing\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Relaxing\">relaxing</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Century_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Century-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> In 1996, the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Los_Angeles_Times\" title=\"Los Angeles Times\">Los Angeles Times</a></i> deemed the Dreamachine \"the most interesting object\" in Burroughs' major visual retrospective <i>Ports of Entry</i> at <a href=\"/wiki/Los_Angeles_County_Museum_of_Art\" title=\"Los Angeles County Museum of Art\">LACMA</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\nThe Dreamachine is the subject of the <a href=\"/wiki/National_Film_Board_of_Canada\" title=\"National Film Board of Canada\">National Film Board of Canada</a> 2008 feature documentary film <i><a href=\"/wiki/FLicKeR_(film)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"FLicKeR (film)\">FLicKeR</a></i> by <a href=\"/wiki/Nik_Sheehan\" title=\"Nik Sheehan\">Nik Sheehan</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Use\">Use</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Dreamachine&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Use\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>A Dreamachine is \"viewed\" with the eyes closed: the pulsating light stimulates the <a href=\"/wiki/Optic_nerve\" title=\"Optic nerve\">optic nerve</a> and thus alters the brain's electrical oscillations. Users experience increasingly bright, complex patterns of color behind their closed eyelids (a similar effect may be experienced when travelling as a passenger in a car or bus; close your eyes as the vehicle passes through flickering shadows cast by roadside trees, or under a close-set line of streetlights or tunnel striplights). The patterns become shapes and symbols, swirling around, until the user feels surrounded by colors. It is claimed that by using a Dreamachine one may enter a <a href=\"/wiki/Hypnagogic\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Hypnagogic\">hypnagogic state</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>  This experience may sometimes be quite intense, but to escape from it, one needs only to open one's eyes.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Cecil_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Cecil-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\nThe Dreamachine may be dangerous for persons with <a href=\"/wiki/Photosensitive_epilepsy\" title=\"Photosensitive epilepsy\">photosensitive epilepsy</a> or other <a href=\"/wiki/Anxiety_disorder\" title=\"Anxiety disorder\">nervous disorders</a>. It is thought that one out of 10,000 adults will experience a seizure while viewing the device; about twice as many children will have a similar ill effect.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Allen_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Allen-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Dreamachine&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Jan_Evangelista_Purkyn%C4%9B\" title=\"Jan Evangelista Purkyn\u011b\">Jan E. Purkyn\u011b</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Mind_machine\" title=\"Mind machine\">Mind machine</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Dreamachine&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Cecil-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Cecil_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Cecil_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Cecil, Paul (March 2000). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.permuted.org.uk/dream1.htm\">\"Everything is Permuted\"</a>. <i>Flickers of the Dreamachine</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2007-03-27</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Flickers+of+the+Dreamachine&amp;rft.atitle=Everything+is+Permuted&amp;rft.date=2000-03&amp;rft.aulast=Cecil&amp;rft.aufirst=Paul&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.permuted.org.uk%2Fdream1.htm&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADreamachine\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Century-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Century_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Century_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Century, Dan (December 2000). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.legendsmagazine.net/105/brion.htm\">\"Brion Gysin and his Wonderful Dreamachine\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/Legends_Magazine\" title=\"Legends Magazine\">Legends Magazine</a></i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2007-03-27</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Brion+Gysin+and+his+Wonderful+Dreamachine&amp;rft.pub=%27%27Legends+Magazine%27%27&amp;rft.date=2000-12&amp;rft.aulast=Century&amp;rft.aufirst=Dan&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.legendsmagazine.net%2F105%2Fbrion.htm&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADreamachine\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a href=\"/wiki/Christopher_Knight_(art_critic)\" title=\"Christopher Knight (art critic)\">Knight, C.</a>, <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://articles.latimes.com/1996-08-01/entertainment/ca-29922_1_modern-art\">\"The Art of Randomness\"</a>, <i>Los Angeles Times</i>, Aug 1, 1996.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.flickerflicker.com\">Film Web site</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Kerekes, David (2003). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.cz/books?id=pq_o5ky6MiYC&amp;printsec=frontcover&amp;source=gbs_ge_summary_r&amp;cad=0#v=onepage&amp;q&amp;f=false\"><i>Headpress 25: William Burroughs &amp; the Flicker Machine</i></a>. Headpress. p.&#160;13. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/1-900486-26-1\" title=\"Special:BookSources/1-900486-26-1\">1-900486-26-1</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Headpress+25%3A+William+Burroughs+%26+the+Flicker+Machine&amp;rft.pages=13&amp;rft.pub=Headpress&amp;rft.date=2003&amp;rft.isbn=1-900486-26-1&amp;rft.aulast=Kerekes&amp;rft.aufirst=David&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.cz%2Fbooks%3Fid%3Dpq_o5ky6MiYC%26printsec%3Dfrontcover%26source%3Dgbs_ge_summary_r%26cad%3D0%23v%3Donepage%26q%26f%3Dfalse&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADreamachine\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Allen-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Allen_6-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Allen, Mark (January 20, 2005). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/20/garden/20mach.html?ex=1264050000&amp;en=2ead60550b324624&amp;ei=5088&amp;partner=rssnyt\">\"D\u00e9cor by Timothy Leary\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_New_York_Times\" title=\"The New York Times\">The New York Times</a></i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2007-03-27</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+New+York+Times&amp;rft.atitle=D%C3%A9cor+by+Timothy+Leary&amp;rft.date=2005-01-20&amp;rft.aulast=Allen&amp;rft.aufirst=Mark&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F2005%2F01%2F20%2Fgarden%2F20mach.html%3Fex%3D1264050000%26en%3D2ead60550b324624%26ei%3D5088%26partner%3Drssnyt&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADreamachine\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Dreamachine&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Don_Bolles_(musician)\" title=\"Don Bolles (musician)\">Bolles, D.</a>, <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://juniperhills.net/weekly.pdf\">\"Dream Weaver\"</a>, <i><a href=\"/wiki/LA_Weekly\" title=\"LA Weekly\">LA Weekly</a></i>, Jul. 26\u2013Aug. 1, 1996.</li>\n<li>Cecil, Paul. (2000). <i><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.permuted.org.uk/Flickers.htm\">Flickers Of The Dreamachine</a></i>. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/1-899598-03-0\" title=\"Special:BookSources/1-899598-03-0\">1-899598-03-0</a> <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.permuted.org.uk/dmpdown.htm\">Download excerpts</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Further_reading\">Further reading</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Dreamachine&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: Further reading\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><cite class=\"citation web\">McKenzie, Andrew M. (1989). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.discogs.com/release/582394\">\"The Hafler Trio &amp; Thee Temple Ov Psychick Youth - Present Brion Gysin's Dreamachine\"</a>. Belgium: KK records<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2010-10-21</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=The+Hafler+Trio+%26+Thee+Temple+Ov+Psychick+Youth+-+Present+Brion+Gysin%27s+Dreamachine&amp;rft.place=Belgium&amp;rft.pub=KK+records&amp;rft.date=1989&amp;rft.aulast=McKenzie&amp;rft.aufirst=Andrew+M.&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.discogs.com%2Frelease%2F58